      <body>
         <div xml:id="main">
            <head type="incipit">
               <supplied reason="XTF-compatibility">Melbourne ¶ 28 Dec. 1885. ¶  ¶ From "Nature" ¶  I learn, dear Sir Joseph, that Kew acquired the mainset of the Forster's plants from Liverpool. Would you favor me with a small fragment of  ¶ Myoporum ...</supplied>
            </head>
            <p rend="number" xml:lang="en">85.12.28b </p>
            <p rend="correspondent" xml:lang="en">To Joseph Hooker</p>
            <p rend="location" xml:lang="en">RBG Kew, Kew Correspondence, Australia, Mueller, 1882-1890, ff. 163-4.</p>
            <space dim="vertical" unit="lines" quantity="1"/>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva, Geneva; font-size: 12pt; text-align: end; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <note xml:id="ftn1" type="footnote" n="1">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva, Geneva; margin-left: 0.3346in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3346in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">
                     <seg style="font-style: italic; ">Annotated in purple pencil by W. Thiselton-Dyer</seg>: And <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>12.2.86 <seg style="font-style: italic; ">[letter not found].</seg>
                  </p>
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva, Geneva; margin-left: 0.3346in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3346in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">
                     <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>
                     <seg style="font-style: italic; ">Annotated in blue pencil, above Thiselton-Dyer's annotation, by J. Hooker:</seg> Prof O. <seg style="font-style: italic; ">[i.e. Daniel Oliver]</seg>.</p>
               </note>Melbourne</p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva, Geneva; font-size: 12pt; text-align: end; "
               xml:lang="en">28 Dec. 1885.</p>
            <space dim="vertical" unit="lines" quantity="1"/>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva, Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>From "Nature"<note xml:id="ftn2" type="footnote" n="2">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva, Geneva; margin-left: 0.3346in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3346in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">Hemsley (1885).</p>
               </note> I learn, dear Sir Joseph, that Kew acquired the mainset of the Forster's plants from Liverpool. Would you favor me with a small fragment of <seg style="">
                  <hi rend="underline">
                     <name key="Myoporum%20pubescens">Myoporum pubescens</name>
                  </hi>
               </seg> &amp; M. <seg style="">
                  <hi rend="underline">crassifolium</hi>
               </seg> for examination,<note xml:id="ftn3" type="footnote" n="3">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva, Geneva; margin-left: 0.3346in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3346in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">
                     <seg style="font-style: italic; ">Small pencilled</seg> 'x' <seg style="font-style: italic; ">above</seg> crassifolium <seg style="font-style: italic; ">and a pencilled annotation in the left margin, f. 163 front</seg>
                     <seg style="font-style: italic; ">[in Daniel Oliver’s hand?]:</seg> only x in F's Herb. <seg style="font-style: italic; ">Vertical blue pencil line in left margin next to </seg>Would you favor ... examination.</p>
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva, Geneva; margin-left: 0.3346in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3346in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">
                     <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>
                     <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>
                     <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>See also M to W. Carruthers, 3 December 1885.</p>
               </note> as that would be important for my monography of the <name key="Myoporinae">Myoporinae</name>. If no part of these plants can be spared, would you let me know your opinion concerning them? “Botanices insula” means probably “Botany Bay”; in that case it must have come from Solander.<note xml:id="ftn4" type="footnote" n="4">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva, Geneva; margin-left: 0.3346in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3346in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">
                     <seg style="font-style: italic; ">M. crassifolium</seg> is listed in G. Forster (1786a) as species 240, p. 44, where it is listed as from 'Botanices infula'.</p>
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva, Geneva; margin-left: 0.3346in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3346in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">
                     <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>'Botanices insula' is a small islet near New Caledonia. See G. Forster (1777), vol. 2, <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>p. 439, entry for 30 September 1774: </p>
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva, Geneva; font-size: 9pt; margin-left: 0.5in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: 0in; "
                     xml:lang="en">Captain Cook gave this little islet the name of Botany Island, because it contained in so small a space a <seg style="font-style: italic; ">flora</seg> of nearly thirty species, among which we saw several new ones. Its situation is nearly 22° 28' S. and 167° 16' E. </p>
               </note>
            </p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva, Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>
               <name key="Senecio%20angustifolius">Senecio angustifolius</name> can now also perhaps be cleared up. Perhaps it is Erechtites<note xml:id="ftn5" type="footnote" n="5">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva, Geneva; margin-left: 0.3346in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3346in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">Erechthites?</p>
               </note> quadridentata.<note xml:id="ftn6" type="footnote" n="6">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva, Geneva; margin-left: 0.3346in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3346in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">
                     <seg style="font-style: italic; ">Blue pencil line and annotation [unidentified hand] in lead pencil in left margin, f 163 back, next to </seg>Senecio ... quadridentata: '= Senecio lautus Forst. [forma]'.</p>
               </note>
            </p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva, Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>Mr Dyer wrote to me about any future Professorship of Botany here.<note xml:id="ftn7" type="footnote" n="7">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva, Geneva; margin-left: 0.3346in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3346in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">Letter not found, but see M to W. Thiselton-Dyer, 19 September 1885.</p>
               </note> In my life-time probably none will be established “per se”, as the University has more pressing demands; thus perhaps a Professorship for <seg style="">
                  <hi rend="underline">Agriculture</hi>
               </seg> may become established, which would be more to the mind of the breadwinning colonists.<note xml:id="ftn8" type="footnote" n="8">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva, Geneva; margin-left: 0.3346in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3346in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">thus perhaps... colonists <seg style="font-style: italic; ">note in right hand margin, f 163 back, position indicated by ms marks.</seg>
                  </p>
               </note> and even if an endowment for it specially was made, I could as little accept it as you could spare time for lecturing at the London University. Simply, because I had no time for lecturing, I declined a position on the Melbourne University as far back as 1854.<note xml:id="ftn9" type="footnote" n="9">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva, Geneva; margin-left: 0.3346in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3346in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">No evidence of M's being offered such a position has been found.</p>
               </note> I am however a hon. Examiner of the Melb, Sydney and Adelaide University, looked just through 14 examination papers from Sydney. Will write you soon more fully on <name key="Livistona">Livistona</name>s of Australia.<note xml:id="ftn10" type="footnote" n="10">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva, Geneva; margin-left: 0.3346in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3346in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">I am however... of Australia <seg style="font-style: italic; ">is a marginal note in the left margin, f 164 front with position indicated by *.</seg> M was appointed an examiner in the newly established Faculty of Medicine at the University of Adelaide on 16 October 1885 (Council minutes, Adelaide University Archives).</p>
               </note>
            </p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva, Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>I am sending your son<note xml:id="ftn11" type="footnote" n="11">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva, Geneva; margin-left: 0.3346in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3346in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">Brian Hooker.</p>
               </note> on his desire just a cither, so that he can keep up his musical enjoyments in the solitude. I am glad, that one of my friends helped him to his present position, which has become financially already much improved.</p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva, Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>Next week we will have our annual meeting of the geographic Society here. It taxes me much with extra-work.</p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva, Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>If you can send me the information on Myoporum <seg style="">
                  <hi rend="underline">soon</hi>
               </seg>, I shall feel much obliged. </p>
            <p rend="valediction"
               style="font-family: Geneva, Geneva; font-size: 12pt; margin-left: 1.75in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: 0in; "
               xml:lang="en">Wishing you a happy newyear, </p>
            <p rend="valediction"
               style="font-family: Geneva, Geneva; font-size: 12pt; margin-left: 1.75in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: 0in; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>I remain</p>
            <p rend="valediction"
               style="font-family: Geneva, Geneva; font-size: 12pt; margin-left: 1.75in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: 0in; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>regardfully your</p>
            <p rend="valediction"
               style="font-family: Geneva, Geneva; font-size: 12pt; margin-left: 1.75in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: 0in; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>Ferd. von Mueller.<note xml:id="ftn12" type="footnote" n="12">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva, Geneva; margin-left: 0.3346in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3346in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">A note from Daniel Oliver with comments about the plants mentioned in the text is bound at f. 165. Oliver judged Forster's <seg style="font-style: italic; ">
                        <name key="Myoporum%20crassifolium">Myoporum crassifolium</name>
                     </seg> to be '<seg style="">
                        <hi rend="underline">M. [Laetum]</hi>
                     </seg>' He included 'a small leaf &amp; calyx for F. v. Mueller', and observed that 'We are obliged to accept the localities attached to the Forster plants with great caution'.</p>
               </note>
            </p>
            <space dim="vertical" unit="lines" quantity="1"/>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva, Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">Mr C. Moore is very jealous of Dr Woolls's innocent little publication.<note xml:id="ftn13" type="footnote" n="13">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva, Geneva; margin-left: 0.3346in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3346in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">Woolls (1885).</p>
               </note> Its issue was <seg style="">
                  <hi rend="underline">not</hi>
               </seg> instigated by <seg style="">
                  <hi rend="underline">me</hi>
               </seg>. But publications of one sort or the other will arise in these colonies now by amateurs and others. Woolls is much over 70; so this will probably be his "Swan-song"<note xml:id="ftn14" type="footnote" n="14">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva, Geneva; margin-left: 0.3346in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3346in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">Woolls is much ... Swan-song" <seg style="font-style: italic; ">is a marginal note, position indicted by manuscript marks</seg>, <seg style="font-style: italic; ">in right margin, f 164 bac</seg>k.</p>
               </note>
            </p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva, Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>I was much pleased with the figure of Boronia heterophylla[.]<note xml:id="ftn15" type="footnote" n="15">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva, Geneva; margin-left: 0.3346in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3346in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">
                     <seg style="">J. Hooker (1865-1904)</seg>, vol. 111, t. 6845 (published 1 November 1885). Hooker in his notes to the illustration did not mention fragrance.</p>
               </note> Do you not find the flowers very fragrant?<note xml:id="ftn16" type="footnote" n="16">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva, Geneva; margin-left: 0.3346in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3346in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">I was ... fragrant <seg style="font-style: italic; ">is a marginal note in left margin, f 163 front.</seg>
                  </p>
               </note>
            </p>
            <space dim="vertical" unit="lines" quantity="1"/>
